The automatic doors slid open with a soft whoosh, and Milo the golden retriever paused on the threshold, nose twitching. The vet clinic smelled like a strange mix of disinfectant, treats, and the faintest hint of other animals who had passed through earlier. His tail gave a cautious wag as his owner gently encouraged him forward.
Inside, Milo’s nails clicked lightly on the clean floor. A cat in a carrier stared at him with wide, offended eyes, and Milo politely looked away, pretending he hadn’t noticed. The receptionist leaned over the counter with a smile, offering him a biscuit. Milo accepted it with great seriousness, as if this were part of an important diplomatic exchange.
When the vet called his name, Milo trotted into the exam room, curiosity winning over nerves. The vet knelt beside him, speaking in a calm, cheerful voice while checking his ears, his heartbeat, and the pads of his paws. Milo sat very still, tail sweeping the floor like a slow metronome. Every so often, he glanced up at his owner as if to say, I’m being very brave.
After a quick vaccination and a well-earned cuddle from the vet, Milo strutted out of the clinic with a new bandana around his neck and a spring in his step. The world outside smelled fresher, brighter — and he was certain he had just completed a heroic mission.
